context: Dell's <a0_0><b5_0>manufacturing<b5_0/><a0_0/> process covers assembly, software installation, functional testing (including "burn-in"), and quality control. Throughout most of the company's history, Dell manufactured desktop machines <b6_0>in-house<b6_0/> and contracted out manufacturing of base notebooks for configuration <a1_0>in-house<a1_0/>. The company's approach has changed, as cited in the <a2_0><b7_0>2006<b7_0/><a2_0/> Annual Report, which states, "We are continuing to expand our use of original design manufacturing partnerships and manufacturing outsourcing relationships." <a3_0><b8_0>The Wall Street Journal<b8_0/><a3_0/> reported in September 2008 that "Dell has approached contract computer manufacturers with offers to sell" their plants. By the late 2000s, Dell's "configure to order" approach of manufacturing—delivering individual PCs configured to customer specifications from its US facilities was no longer as efficient or competitive with high-volume <a4_0><b9_0>Asian<b9_0/><a4_0/> contract manufacturers as PCs became powerful low-cost commodities.
